3
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:52,710
Hold it, Paulie!

4
00:01:52,710 --> 00:01:55,210
You won't get away this time!

5
00:01:55,210 --> 00:01:57,800
And I'm asking you to wait just a bit longer!

6
00:01:57,800 --> 00:01:59,290
Who's that?

7
00:01:59,290 --> 00:02:00,470
That's Paulie.

8
00:02:00,470 --> 00:02:02,510
He's running from debt collectors again.

9
00:02:02,510 --> 00:02:04,010
Pay back the money!

10
00:02:04,010 --> 00:02:07,390
Like I said, I don't have any cash today!

11
00:02:07,390 --> 00:02:10,520
That's not gonna cut it!

12
00:02:10,520 --> 00:02:13,110
Damn, they won't let up!

13
00:02:13,110 --> 00:02:15,030
Huh? Perfect! Yagara bulls!

14
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:20,570
Rope Action!

15
00:02:22,410 --> 00:02:23,410
Ah!

16
00:02:23,410 --> 00:02:25,870
He's a Galley-La shipwright!

17
00:02:25,870 --> 00:02:29,120
Sorry, but I'd like to borrow
one of your yagaras for a bit!

18
00:02:29,120 --> 00:02:31,610
Round Turn!

19
00:02:55,790 --> 00:02:57,990
Damn! He got away again!

20
00:02:57,990 --> 00:03:00,790
Well then, everyone, take care!

21
00:03:00,790 --> 00:03:03,950
Let's run around again soon!

22
00:03:03,950 --> 00:03:05,450
Dammit!

23
00:03:05,450 --> 00:03:10,230
Seriously though! You came
in the nick of time!

24
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:17,880
What a relief! He's one of
your shipwrights, right?

25
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:19,480
That's right.

26
00:03:19,480 --> 00:03:21,300
Hey! Thanks!

27
00:03:21,930 --> 00:03:24,260
That money belongs to us!

28
00:03:24,260 --> 00:03:25,350
What? Money?

29
00:03:25,350 --> 00:03:27,800
Let's see...

30
00:03:29,810 --> 00:03:35,310
Hey...! Huh? Hey!

31
00:03:35,310 --> 00:03:36,980
Get back here!

32
00:03:36,980 --> 00:03:38,280
That jerk!

33
00:03:38,280 --> 00:03:40,870
I'll bring him ba– Huh?

34
00:03:42,490 --> 00:03:43,660
I got this.

35
00:03:43,660 --> 00:03:47,620
What? A... A pigeon?

36
00:03:47,620 --> 00:03:50,940
Ow, ow, ow, ow, ow! Hey, hey, let me go!

37
00:03:50,940 --> 00:03:53,080
What the hell are you doing?!

38
00:03:53,080 --> 00:03:57,040
I'm not gonna run, man! I get it, okay?!

39
00:03:57,040 --> 00:03:58,550
Let go of my ear!

40
00:03:59,780 --> 00:04:03,000
Here I was lucky enough to find
all this money just now...!

41
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:04,930
You'll regret this, Lucci!

42
00:04:04,930 --> 00:04:09,300
Don't pay back your debts
with other people's money, you ignoramus!

43
00:04:09,300 --> 00:04:11,180
But I found this money!

44
00:04:11,180 --> 00:04:14,100
You think that story will fly?!

45
00:04:14,100 --> 00:04:17,790
It just happened to be
on the yagara that I borrowed!

46
00:04:17,790 --> 00:04:19,690
They're back.

47
00:04:20,290 --> 00:04:22,870
Well, I'm happy for you, Usopp!

48
00:04:22,870 --> 00:04:26,990
Don't act like you've got no skin
in the game! It's our 200 million belly!

49
00:04:27,710 --> 00:04:32,190
That's right! Why the hell weren't you
the first one to go get it back?!

50
00:04:32,190 --> 00:04:34,870
But that pigeon said he'd go.

51
00:04:34,870 --> 00:04:37,600
Well... I'm sorry.

52
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:40,510
We should deal with
our own idiot employees...

53
00:04:40,510 --> 00:04:43,900
otherwise, it'd create
undue tension if you'd caught him.

54
00:04:43,900 --> 00:04:48,510
Well, consider yourselves lucky your money
wasn't stolen by the Franky Family.

55
00:04:48,510 --> 00:04:50,430
Hmm... That's true, but...

56
00:04:50,430 --> 00:04:52,370
Yeah, that's true, that's true.

57
00:04:54,230 --> 00:04:59,070
So then, who were those
weird-looking guys from earlier?

58
00:04:59,070 --> 00:05:02,400
The Franky Family is a group
of ship dismantlers.

59
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:07,370
Dismantlers? They seemed more like
thugs than honest craftsmen.

60
00:05:07,370 --> 00:05:11,600
Right. They're also bounty hunters on the side.

61
00:05:11,600 --> 00:05:16,000
They cause quite the stir every time
they discover pirates have entered the city.

62
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:17,830
They're a public nuisance.

63
00:05:17,830 --> 00:05:23,380
If they take out the pirates who
come to town, they also get their ship, see?

64
00:05:23,380 --> 00:05:26,930
They dismantle the ship
and sell the usable lumber.

65
00:05:26,930 --> 00:05:29,890
That's just the Franky Family business.

66
00:05:29,890 --> 00:05:34,060
What crawled up their butts?!
Are they trying to dismantle all pirate crews?!

67
00:05:34,060 --> 00:05:37,020
Well, run afoul of them
and not even your bones will remain.

68
00:05:37,020 --> 00:05:39,770
But they didn't look that strong.

69
00:05:40,350 --> 00:05:42,110
They're just lackeys.

70
00:05:42,840 --> 00:05:48,530
Think what you will of them, but never
underestimate their devoted boss, Franky.

71
00:05:51,450 --> 00:05:54,010
We got him, Mr. Iceburg.

72
00:05:54,010 --> 00:05:56,000
Again, you're hurting my ear!

73
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:57,710
Good work, Lucci.

74
00:05:57,710 --> 00:06:01,420
We're sorry this birdbrain caused you trouble.

75
00:06:01,420 --> 00:06:03,000
Ah! It spoke again!

76
00:06:04,300 --> 00:06:05,550
Ow!

77
00:06:05,550 --> 00:06:08,510
Now, apologize to them, Paulie!

78
00:06:09,900 --> 00:06:12,500
That pigeon's doing all the talking!

79
00:06:12,500 --> 00:06:14,720
It's like he's speaking for the guy with the hat.

80
00:06:14,720 --> 00:06:17,690
In any case, I'm so glad the money's back!

81
00:06:17,690 --> 00:06:20,480
Hey, so the money belonged to you?

82
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:22,240
I brought it back for you.

83
00:06:22,240 --> 00:06:23,690
Oh, thanks!

84
00:06:23,690 --> 00:06:26,110
Thank me with finder's fee of ten percent.

85
00:06:28,690 --> 00:06:30,620
Sorry 'bout that, sir.

86
00:06:32,100 --> 00:06:38,080
This guy's gambling debt is so high,
he's turned greedy and forgot his manners.

87
00:06:38,080 --> 00:06:40,630
Okay, but why are you talking?!

88
00:06:40,630 --> 00:06:43,920
You cagey bastard!
Stop running your mouth, Lucci!

89
00:06:43,920 --> 00:06:45,550
You've crossed the line!

90
00:06:46,210 --> 00:06:48,550
Rope Action:

91
00:06:51,300 --> 00:06:54,100
Bowline Knot!

92
00:06:57,430 --> 00:06:59,390
Discipline:

93
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:05,110
Wait! Oh, no! He's serious!

94
00:07:07,890 --> 00:07:10,570
Fly Fishing!

95
00:07:13,500 --> 00:07:15,330
I-Is he okay?

96
00:07:16,010 --> 00:07:18,290
Well, this always happens.

97
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:23,670
Whoa! L-L-Look at that!

98
00:07:23,670 --> 00:07:27,760
He absorbed the impact with just one arm!

99
00:07:30,200 --> 00:07:33,280
His fingers dug into the ground!

100
00:07:33,280 --> 00:07:36,350
Wh-What kind of fingers does he have?

101
00:07:36,350 --> 00:07:40,600
What sort of shipwrights
do they have working here?

102
00:07:42,290 --> 00:07:44,150
Hey! You, with the goggles!

103
00:07:44,150 --> 00:07:46,110
Huh?

104
00:07:46,110 --> 00:07:48,610
Hey, think about it carefully.

105
00:07:48,610 --> 00:07:52,060
The only one who ever
mocked or provoked you

106
00:07:52,060 --> 00:07:53,420
was that pigeon!

107
00:07:59,190 --> 00:08:00,750
Okay, but...

108
00:08:00,750 --> 00:08:04,250
Lucci's the one who hit me!

109
00:08:04,250 --> 00:08:08,630
The pigeon can't hit you himself,
so he had that guy do it!

110
00:08:08,630 --> 00:08:10,460
Hey, pigeon!

111
00:08:11,380 --> 00:08:14,590
Fight your own battles!

112
00:08:14,590 --> 00:08:16,180
Say something!

113
00:08:22,770 --> 00:08:25,890
Oh? You wanna fight?
Bring it on, you bastard!

114
00:08:25,890 --> 00:08:27,900
Stop it, Paulie.

115
00:08:29,320 --> 00:08:31,820
Well, sorry for the fuss.

116
00:08:31,820 --> 00:08:35,180
I'm Rob L– N-No, I mean, Hattori the pigeon.

117
00:08:35,180 --> 00:08:40,240
And this is Rob Lucci, one of
the workers here. Nice to meet you!

118
00:08:40,240 --> 00:08:44,670
Oh? He just about introduced himself
as if he were the human!

119
00:08:44,670 --> 00:08:48,130
Aha! Yeah, I know this trick!
That's ventriloquism, isn't it?!

120
00:08:48,130 --> 00:08:51,310
Whoa! Seriously?! Then you
really were the one mocking him!

121
00:08:51,310 --> 00:08:54,490
You're really, really good! I didn't notice!

122
00:08:54,490 --> 00:08:57,600
Stop. Don't make a big deal of it.

123
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:02,540
He's a weirdo who can't
talk to people normally.

124
00:09:04,810 --> 00:09:08,020
Wait a sec! What's up with you, lady?!

125
00:09:08,020 --> 00:09:09,480
Who... me?

126
00:09:09,480 --> 00:09:11,240
What a hussy!

127
00:09:12,010 --> 00:09:13,380
Huh?

128
00:09:13,380 --> 00:09:18,200
You're showing off your legs way too much!

129
00:09:18,200 --> 00:09:22,700
This is a workplace for men!
What possessed you to dress like that?!

130
00:09:22,700 --> 00:09:25,550
Now, Paulie, calm down.

131
00:09:30,750 --> 00:09:32,720
You too, Kalifa!

132
00:09:32,720 --> 00:09:35,600
You should know better
than to wear scandalous clothes!

133
00:09:36,410 --> 00:09:39,800
How many times do I have to
tell you?! Wear pants! Long pants!

134
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:40,850
What the heck...?

135
00:09:40,850 --> 00:09:42,210
Long pants?

136
00:09:42,210 --> 00:09:44,100
He's a weirdo too!

137
00:09:44,810 --> 00:09:48,810
Well, that was fun. Let's open
the gate and head inside.

138
00:09:59,700 --> 00:10:05,890
Hard to believe the size of this gate!
And it's manually operated?!

139
00:10:05,890 --> 00:10:08,170
Can those two weirdos open it by themselves?

140
00:10:11,090 --> 00:10:13,290
Whoa! It's moving!

141
00:10:13,290 --> 00:10:16,280
Well, each dock has only
five shipwright foremen.

142
00:10:16,280 --> 00:10:20,430
Strange as they are, their skills earned
them their spots as Dock One foremen.

143
00:10:21,510 --> 00:10:23,810
Kaku, the man from earlier, is one of them.

144
00:10:23,810 --> 00:10:26,640
What matters in this world is
how one plies their trade.

145
00:10:27,250 --> 00:10:29,500
They're weird, but so what?

146
00:10:29,500 --> 00:10:30,750
Yeah, they are weird.

147
00:10:30,750 --> 00:10:32,570
Ah! It's starting to open!

148
00:10:32,570 --> 00:10:36,990
And keep hold of your money.
There shouldn't be thieves here, but still...

149
00:10:37,900 --> 00:10:42,100
Well, it's partially my fault.
Sorry for the trouble.

150
00:10:42,100 --> 00:10:43,660
Hey, Luffy!

151
00:10:43,160 --> 00:10:43,660
Huh?

152
00:10:43,660 --> 00:10:46,480
Make sure you guard me good!

153
00:10:46,480 --> 00:10:48,490
Okay, don't worry! Leave it to me!

154
00:10:48,490 --> 00:10:49,960
I'm worried.

155
00:10:49,290 --> 00:10:49,960
Leave it to me!

156
00:10:49,960 --> 00:10:54,380
What you see here is Dock One,
the core of Galley-La Company,

157
00:10:54,380 --> 00:10:56,960
where we handle our most challenging orders.

158
00:10:56,960 --> 00:10:59,150
Here, come inside.

159
00:10:59,150 --> 00:11:01,990
– Wow!
– Wow!

160
00:11:03,220 --> 00:11:05,260
Whoa!

161
00:11:13,400 --> 00:11:17,780
Wow! It's all huge!

162
00:11:18,490 --> 00:11:22,040
This shipyard's even more incredible
when seen up close!

163
00:11:22,040 --> 00:11:23,410
Yeah!

164
00:11:22,660 --> 00:11:23,410
True!

165
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:28,700
Oh? They're building
a huge galleon! Who's it for?

166
00:11:28,700 --> 00:11:30,250
There're so many craftsmen.

167
00:11:30,250 --> 00:11:32,770
Now, this way.

168
00:11:35,740 --> 00:11:37,800
Oh, it's Mr. Iceburg!

169
00:11:37,800 --> 00:11:40,670
Hey! The boss is here!

170
00:11:40,670 --> 00:11:43,320
Good morning, Mr. Iceburg!

171
00:11:43,320 --> 00:11:44,680
Good morning!

172
00:11:44,680 --> 00:11:48,200
Boss! Could you take a look
at how the hull turned out?

173
00:11:48,200 --> 00:11:49,640
Sure! I'll come by later!

174
00:11:49,640 --> 00:11:52,680
Nice day today, Mr. Iceburg!

175
00:11:52,680 --> 00:11:55,140
Well, hi there. Everything going well?

176
00:11:55,140 --> 00:11:57,360
Yes, sir! They're going pretty well!

177
00:11:57,360 --> 00:12:01,460
Whoa! Everyone likes Iceboss.

178
00:12:01,460 --> 00:12:04,660
Indeed they do. Skill means
everything in this city.

179
00:12:05,230 --> 00:12:09,700
Shipbuilding has always been
this island's main industry,

180
00:12:09,700 --> 00:12:12,590
and seven shipyards were
competing for contracts.

181
00:12:13,220 --> 00:12:17,540
He eventually charmed the shipwrights
with his genius craftsmanship.

182
00:12:17,540 --> 00:12:22,510
Five years ago, he managed to merge
all seven companies, and the rest is history.

183
00:12:22,510 --> 00:12:24,720
That's the current Galley-La Company.

184
00:12:25,400 --> 00:12:28,600
His passion and skill for
shipbuilding hasn't waned,

185
00:12:28,600 --> 00:12:31,850
and he's never lost
the respect of the shipwrights.

186
00:12:31,850 --> 00:12:34,900
And, because the craftsmen
take pride in their skills,

187
00:12:34,900 --> 00:12:38,440
they neither give in to pirates nor authority.

188
00:12:39,400 --> 00:12:42,000
That's how we run things here.

189
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:42,860
Wha...?

190
00:12:42,860 --> 00:12:46,300
Hey, old guy. I heard you're
a top-notch shipwright.

191
00:12:46,300 --> 00:12:48,120
Wanna be a pirate with me?

192
00:12:48,120 --> 00:12:50,170
Wanna run that by us again, jackass?!

193
00:12:50,170 --> 00:12:51,380
H-How brazen!

194
00:12:51,380 --> 00:12:53,930
Hey, now. He's always like this.

195
00:12:53,930 --> 00:12:55,000
Sorry 'bout that.

196
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:59,090
Well... you guys don't have
a single shipwright aboard your ship?

197
00:12:59,090 --> 00:12:59,900
That's right.

198
00:12:59,900 --> 00:13:04,680
We came to this island to get
our ship fixed and find a new crewmate.

199
00:13:04,680 --> 00:13:07,400
It's true that we have
a whole slew of shipwrights,

200
00:13:07,400 --> 00:13:10,470
but I wonder if any fancy the life of a pirate.

201
00:13:10,470 --> 00:13:14,230
If there's anyone here who's
willing to sail with you, they're yours.

202
00:13:14,230 --> 00:13:19,190
Really?! You're pretty generous!
Are you sure you don't wanna come, pops?

203
00:13:19,190 --> 00:13:22,060
Well, I can't. I'm the mayor.

204
00:13:22,060 --> 00:13:23,990
Blow it off!

205
00:13:25,670 --> 00:13:30,490
By the way, is there actually a woman
named Nico Robin on your ship?

206
00:13:30,490 --> 00:13:31,330
There is!

207
00:13:31,330 --> 00:13:34,290
She's really smart.

208
00:13:36,790 --> 00:13:39,340
What? Is something the matter with Robin?

209
00:13:40,260 --> 00:13:40,960
No.

210
00:13:44,720 --> 00:13:48,050
I can't believe just how amazing this is!

211
00:13:48,050 --> 00:13:51,720
Keep that steady! Don't rush! Go slowly!

212
00:13:52,350 --> 00:13:56,190
If we could install a cannon like that,
the Merry would be more– Huh?

213
00:13:56,190 --> 00:13:58,440
Whoa! A demi-culverin!

214
00:13:58,940 --> 00:14:04,400
So cool! It's so long... and shiny!

215
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:07,360
I'd give anything to fire
something like that just once.

216
00:14:07,360 --> 00:14:08,570
Now's our chance.

217
00:14:09,610 --> 00:14:13,600
It looks like it's made of copper.
That must be expensive!

218
00:14:13,600 --> 00:14:16,080
I wonder if they'd let me try firing it.

219
00:14:16,080 --> 00:14:20,450
Oh, wait. We've now got 300 million belly.

220
00:14:20,450 --> 00:14:23,590
We can afford to buy a few of those cannons!

221
00:14:30,300 --> 00:14:31,570
Hm?

222
00:14:32,780 --> 00:14:35,180
Wasn't someone standing there?

223
00:14:46,780 --> 00:14:47,820
Huh? Kaku!

224
00:14:49,200 --> 00:14:50,540
Where have you been?

225
00:14:50,540 --> 00:14:51,390
An assessment.

226
00:14:51,390 --> 00:14:53,080
Ah! You're the guy from earlier!

227
00:14:53,080 --> 00:14:54,490
So you checked our ship?

228
00:14:54,490 --> 00:14:56,500
Yep, I put my eyeballs to it.

229
00:14:56,500 --> 00:14:59,080
Oh, Mr. Iceburg, you're present.

230
00:14:59,080 --> 00:15:02,250
I'm all caught up. How was it?

231
00:15:02,250 --> 00:15:04,710
In all honesty...

232
00:15:05,420 --> 00:15:08,840
Luffy! Come on down!

233
00:15:24,190 --> 00:15:26,280
What?! Is that true?!

234
00:15:26,280 --> 00:15:28,900
If this is a lie, you'll pay!

235
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:33,570
A lie has no legs in my line of work.

236
00:15:47,210 --> 00:15:50,050
So, where's Usopp?

237
00:15:50,610 --> 00:15:54,540
He was just over there up until a moment ago.

238
00:15:56,510 --> 00:16:01,080
Hey, you guys!
Don't these cases belong to you?

239
00:16:03,100 --> 00:16:06,300
Ah! Usopp was carrying these!

240
00:16:06,300 --> 00:16:07,320
Yeah, they're ours.

241
00:16:07,320 --> 00:16:09,290
Thanks!

242
00:16:09,290 --> 00:16:14,740
C'mon! Where did you go, Usopp,
leaving all our precious money unattended?!

243
00:16:14,740 --> 00:16:15,200
Money?

244
00:16:15,200 --> 00:16:18,720
Yeah! Those bags hold 200 million belly.

245
00:16:19,620 --> 00:16:21,660
200 million belly?!

246
00:16:21,660 --> 00:16:23,580
Nice one. See ya!

247
00:16:23,580 --> 00:16:26,000
There's no way.

248
00:16:26,700 --> 00:16:29,000
So, how much will it cost?

249
00:16:29,550 --> 00:16:33,090
We can pay as much as you like!
We've got tons of money!

250
00:16:35,470 --> 00:16:41,930
If possible, I'd like her to be stronger,
have more cannons, and be faster!

251
00:16:41,930 --> 00:16:45,890
Can you also stylize the outer hull
with some tasteful engravings?

252
00:16:45,890 --> 00:16:48,270
Could you renovate the interior as well?

253
00:16:48,270 --> 00:16:49,950
Just hold your horses.

254
00:16:50,820 --> 00:16:55,280
You guys have truly been on
one incredible lark after another, right?

255
00:16:56,800 --> 00:16:59,600
You bet we did! We flew into
the sky and fell back down.

256
00:16:59,600 --> 00:17:01,900
We sailed up a mountain
and even got skewered.

257
00:17:01,900 --> 00:17:03,800
We've gone through quite a bit!

258
00:17:03,800 --> 00:17:06,460
So, we'd like to have her fixed good!

259
00:17:07,390 --> 00:17:09,630
Her scars from battle are too deep.

260
00:17:10,810 --> 00:17:13,470
Do you mean it'll take awhile
to complete repairs?

261
00:17:14,260 --> 00:17:15,280
No.

262
00:17:16,050 --> 00:17:19,540
I'll give it to you straight. Your ship...

263
00:17:20,900 --> 00:17:23,890
is beyond repair, even with our expertise.

264
00:17:38,790 --> 00:17:40,780
I'm guessing it's the keel.

265
00:17:40,780 --> 00:17:44,660
Yeah. It's taken a lot of damage.

266
00:17:44,660 --> 00:17:45,890
No way.

267
00:17:46,690 --> 00:17:49,920
But we've been traveling
just fine up until today!

268
00:17:49,920 --> 00:17:54,380
Let's suppose that we
gave it the old college try.

269
00:17:54,380 --> 00:17:58,340
The probability that she
reaches the next island is...

270
00:18:01,400 --> 00:18:02,650
zero.

271
00:18:14,210 --> 00:18:18,030
Merry, are you really...

272
00:18:18,780 --> 00:18:20,280
done sailing?

273
00:18:24,100 --> 00:18:25,660
Well, crap.

274
00:18:26,990 --> 00:18:31,750
I'm sorry, Sanji. I got a little lost in the books.

275
00:18:31,750 --> 00:18:34,500
There's no need to apologize.

276
00:18:34,500 --> 00:18:39,640
I just assumed the one with Robin
was you in your human form.

277
00:18:40,490 --> 00:18:44,180
Then, who in the world was that masked man?

278
00:18:44,180 --> 00:18:46,800
Stranger still, they suddenly disappeared.

279
00:18:46,800 --> 00:18:51,100
Yeah. Robin's scent vanished there too.

280
00:18:52,190 --> 00:18:55,820
It's probably nothing,
but my stomach's in a knot about this.

281
00:18:55,820 --> 00:18:56,900
Huh?

282
00:18:56,900 --> 00:18:58,800
Do you need me to give you a checkup?

283
00:18:58,800 --> 00:19:00,360
I'm not sick!

284
00:19:01,050 --> 00:19:04,410
But I feel like that Aokiji guy
said something about this.

285
00:19:05,200 --> 00:19:07,000
So, what did he say?

286
00:19:07,000 --> 00:19:10,200
He kept alluding to Robin's past.

287
00:19:10,200 --> 00:19:13,540
He also mentioned we'd
someday regret taking her on.

288
00:19:13,540 --> 00:19:15,490
That rings a bell.

289
00:19:15,490 --> 00:19:18,760
But how does this relate
to Robin's disappearance?

290
00:19:19,330 --> 00:19:21,000
I don't know.

291
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:25,010
Anyway, we're getting nowhere like this.
Let's go back to the Merry for now.

292
00:19:26,110 --> 00:19:28,790
If there's no problem, she'll be back soon.

293
00:19:28,790 --> 00:19:30,310
Good point.

294
00:19:49,040 --> 00:19:52,210
You can't fix the Merry?! Why not?!

295
00:19:52,210 --> 00:19:55,340
Aren't you guys amazing shipwrights?!

296
00:19:57,380 --> 00:20:00,290
If you need money, just look!
We've more than enough!

297
00:20:00,290 --> 00:20:02,590
Money's not the issue.

298
00:20:02,590 --> 00:20:07,100
All the money in the world can't
return your ship to its original state.

299
00:20:08,310 --> 00:20:15,270
I'm rather surprised that your crew made it
this far in a ship that's worse for the wear.

300
00:20:15,270 --> 00:20:18,690
What do you mean?!
What's wrong with the Merry?!

301
00:20:18,690 --> 00:20:21,820
Do you know what the keel is, you hussy?

302
00:20:21,820 --> 00:20:23,490
On the bottom of the ship?

303
00:20:23,490 --> 00:20:27,790
That's right. It's the most
crucial piece of wood on the ship.

304
00:20:27,790 --> 00:20:31,040
It supports the ship from stem to stern.

305
00:20:31,040 --> 00:20:35,000
When you build a ship,
you start off by placing the keel.

306
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:37,920
Then the stem, the stern,
and the frame structure—

307
00:20:37,920 --> 00:20:40,800
that'd be the floors,
futtocks, and deck beams...

308
00:20:40,800 --> 00:20:45,300
And you carefully position
each piece of lumber around the keel.

309
00:20:45,300 --> 00:20:47,490
Shipbuilding in a nutshell.

310
00:20:47,490 --> 00:20:51,150
The keel is the very foundation—
the very essence—of a ship's framework.

311
00:20:51,150 --> 00:20:56,810
Once it's damaged beyond repair,
it can't just be replaced.

312
00:20:56,810 --> 00:21:01,030
In other words, replacing the keel
is just building a ship from scratch.

313
00:21:01,030 --> 00:21:04,090
So, no one can fix her anymore.

314
00:21:04,090 --> 00:21:08,030
Your ship is little more than
scrap wood awaiting its fate.

315
00:21:08,030 --> 00:21:10,450
Hey! Don't say it like that!

316
00:21:11,870 --> 00:21:14,000
Whatever. It's the truth.

317
00:21:16,350 --> 00:21:20,300
Okay then! You gotta
build us a ship from scratch!

318
00:21:20,300 --> 00:21:22,890
Build the Going Merry!

319
00:21:24,010 --> 00:21:26,220
That's not possible either.

320
00:21:25,190 --> 00:21:26,220
Why not?

321
00:21:26,220 --> 00:21:32,290
We can build a similar ship, but strictly speaking,
it wouldn't be the same as before.

322
00:21:32,290 --> 00:21:36,230
The reality is that no two ships
can ever be exactly the same.

323
00:21:36,230 --> 00:21:37,400
Meaning what?!

324
00:21:37,400 --> 00:21:41,360
Do any two trees in this world
ever grow in exactly the same way?

325
00:21:42,690 --> 00:21:49,240
A seafaring vessel is mostly wood, so the size and curves
of the ship are determined by the shape of the trees.

326
00:21:50,040 --> 00:21:55,290
That's why an exact duplicate can't be built,
even when using the ship's very blueprint.

327
00:21:55,290 --> 00:21:58,500
Even if we followed a blueprint
to build such a copy,

328
00:21:58,500 --> 00:22:03,390
the crew who knew the old ship best
would undoubtedly feel the difference.

329
00:22:03,390 --> 00:22:05,920
That crew would be you guys!

330
00:22:06,590 --> 00:22:08,470
So, that...

331
00:22:08,470 --> 00:22:13,180
That means we really can't sail
aboard the Going Merry ever again?

332
00:22:13,180 --> 00:22:15,210
You got the gist of it.

333
00:22:15,210 --> 00:22:17,390
Either sail her into a watery grave...

334
00:22:18,070 --> 00:22:20,850
or take her apart lickety split.

335
00:22:23,200 --> 00:22:24,270
A caravel!

336
00:22:24,270 --> 00:22:27,360
Ooh! She's a great ship!

337
00:22:28,700 --> 00:22:30,250
Alright! All done!

338
00:22:30,250 --> 00:22:34,170
Our pirate ship,
the Going Merry, is finally ready!

339
00:22:37,400 --> 00:22:40,290
Well... your ship has reached her end.

340
00:22:40,290 --> 00:22:42,180
This is a good opportunity.

341
00:22:42,180 --> 00:22:44,490
You need to face facts and buy a new ship.

342
00:22:44,490 --> 00:22:48,800
You've got money, right? And I heard
correctly that your ship's a caravel?

343
00:22:49,370 --> 00:22:54,340
Truth be told, she's an older style of ship
and wouldn't handle the journey ahead.

344
00:22:54,340 --> 00:22:56,800
No. I don't intend to get a new ship.

345
00:22:56,800 --> 00:22:58,300
Luffy.

346
00:22:58,300 --> 00:23:00,270
Our...

347
00:23:00,270 --> 00:23:03,240
Our ship is the Going Merry!

348
00:23:03,240 --> 00:23:05,690
If she's repaired, she'll sail!

349
00:23:05,690 --> 00:23:09,320
She'll be okay! Even today,
she sailed with no problem!

350
00:23:09,320 --> 00:23:12,490
And now, out of nowhere,
you say she's done sailing?!

351
00:23:12,490 --> 00:23:14,390
Who would believe that?!

352
00:23:14,390 --> 00:23:20,000
You say this, but she's stronger
than any of you know!

353
00:23:21,280 --> 00:23:23,500
So, you'd sail her until she sinks.

354
00:23:23,500 --> 00:23:25,840
Good grief.

355
00:23:26,500 --> 00:23:30,010
And you call yourself a ship's captain?!

356
00:23:32,480 --> 00:23:35,520
This discussion is over.
Think about it carefully.

357
00:23:35,520 --> 00:23:39,400
Come back when you're ready to buy
a new ship. I'll take care of you.

358
00:23:39,400 --> 00:23:43,280
If you spent the 300 million here,
we'd build you a state-of-the-art ship.

359
00:23:43,280 --> 00:23:45,070
Kalifa!

360
00:23:45,070 --> 00:23:47,800
Here. Please look this over.

361
00:23:47,800 --> 00:23:51,240
This catalog lists new and used models.
Use it as a price reference, too.

362
00:23:51,840 --> 00:23:53,310
Mr. Iceburg!

363
00:23:54,320 --> 00:23:57,080
You have a visitor at the gate.

364
00:23:57,080 --> 00:24:00,400
That World Government official
is here again, it seems.

365
00:24:00,400 --> 00:24:01,790
Shall I turn him away?

366
00:24:02,260 --> 00:24:05,490
Well, sure thing! Tell him I'm not here.

367
00:24:05,490 --> 00:24:09,300
Anyway, you've got
a bad case of bed head, Lulu.

368
00:24:09,300 --> 00:24:11,510
Drat! Pardon me!

369
00:24:12,130 --> 00:24:14,000
Well then, I'll ask him to leave.

370
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:15,610
Y-Yeah, would you?

371
00:24:15,610 --> 00:24:18,430
Hold it, Iceburg.

372
00:24:20,900 --> 00:24:22,850
So you're here after all.

373
00:24:22,850 --> 00:24:26,000
Hey, you guys, hide!
They're government officials!

374
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:26,940
What? O-Okay.

375
00:24:32,830 --> 00:24:36,800
Well, hello there, Corgi. I'm not here today.

376
00:24:36,800 --> 00:24:38,280
Yes, you are!

377
00:24:38,280 --> 00:24:41,850
Look, I came all this way by sea train.

378
00:24:41,850 --> 00:24:43,990
Please don't avoid me.

379
00:24:43,990 --> 00:24:45,040
Hmm?

380
00:24:51,800 --> 00:24:55,390
What do I smell, but the scent of pirates?

381
00:24:55,390 --> 00:24:58,430
Of course it is. But I'm only here to chat.

382
00:24:58,430 --> 00:25:01,100
I hate you! Go home!

383
00:25:01,100 --> 00:25:02,270
Acting like a child?

384
00:25:02,270 --> 00:25:04,270
I'm a fully grown man.

385
00:25:06,900 --> 00:25:09,080
Well, then stop stalling.

386
00:25:09,080 --> 00:25:13,990
You're really going to like what I have
to say. Please just hear me out.

387
00:25:15,530 --> 00:25:18,450
Now, let's go somewhere private.

388
00:25:20,290 --> 00:25:23,890
They keep coming back. How persistent.

389
00:25:23,890 --> 00:25:26,190
What could they want with Mr. Iceburg?

390
00:25:26,190 --> 00:25:30,260
It has nothing to do with us.
It must be something to do with power.

391
00:25:30,260 --> 00:25:31,900
Shall I beat them silly?

392
00:25:31,900 --> 00:25:34,970
Perish the thought.
They're from the World Government.

393
00:25:39,010 --> 00:25:39,680
Hm?

394
00:25:39,680 --> 00:25:41,600
What? What's wrong?

395
00:25:42,600 --> 00:25:46,600
I noticed something about the cases
when I carried them to our hiding spot.

396
00:25:48,400 --> 00:25:50,100
They're pretty light.

397
00:25:50,100 --> 00:25:52,320
What...? Why?

398
00:25:52,850 --> 00:25:58,030
Oh, don't joke like that. They couldn't
be light with all that money in them.

399
00:26:03,660 --> 00:26:05,870
Who was that just now?!

400
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:10,290
You idiots! What's the big fuss?!

401
00:26:11,050 --> 00:26:14,710
Hey, woman! Sitting like that lets me see...!

402
00:26:15,280 --> 00:26:18,550
Don't tell me... There's...

403
00:26:20,200 --> 00:26:22,850
No way...

404
00:26:24,850 --> 00:26:26,850
Two-hundred million belly...!

405
00:26:26,850 --> 00:26:28,810
Gone! It's really gone!

406
00:26:28,810 --> 00:26:32,340
Now that I see them,
these aren't even our briefcases!

407
00:26:33,230 --> 00:26:34,370
Wh-Wh-Wh-What're we gonna do?!

408
00:26:34,370 --> 00:26:37,320
Hey, you guys! What's with the shouting?

409
00:26:37,320 --> 00:26:40,400
Our money is... gone.

410
00:26:40,400 --> 00:26:43,290
It's... totally... gone.

411
00:26:43,290 --> 00:26:44,210
What?!

412
00:26:44,210 --> 00:26:45,640
Paulie! You again?

413
00:26:45,640 --> 00:26:46,580
It wasn't me!

414
00:26:46,580 --> 00:26:47,290
Truthfully?

415
00:26:47,290 --> 00:26:49,100
Why would I lie?!

416
00:26:49,100 --> 00:26:49,870
Are you for real?!

417
00:26:49,870 --> 00:26:50,830
Really for real!

418
00:26:50,840 --> 00:26:52,420
Lies. You're suddenly really for real?

419
00:26:52,420 --> 00:27:00,510
Wait...! This isn't...! Just... just shut up!
I swear... I'm not lying! Honestly!

420
00:26:49,870 --> 00:26:51,510
They're so loud.

421
00:26:51,510 --> 00:26:55,790
At any rate, Kaku, didn't I see you
with the Franky Family earlier?

422
00:26:55,790 --> 00:26:57,700
Hm? How do you mean?

423
00:26:57,700 --> 00:27:00,510
I've not clapped eyes
on the Franky Family all day.

424
00:27:00,510 --> 00:27:05,800
That sure is strange. I swear I saw
your long nose among them.

425
00:27:05,800 --> 00:27:07,480
Hold on a sec, you guys!

426
00:27:07,480 --> 00:27:09,390
That's Usopp!

427
00:27:09,390 --> 00:27:11,480
He was with the Franky Family?!

428
00:27:11,480 --> 00:27:15,850
He was with them, or rather,
he was carried away by them.

429
00:27:15,850 --> 00:27:17,570
They kidnapped him!

430
00:27:17,570 --> 00:27:19,400
Luffy! We need to find him quickly!

431
00:27:19,400 --> 00:27:20,530
Okay!

432
00:27:20,530 --> 00:27:24,160
Hey! Wait! Where're you gonna look, Luffy?!

433
00:27:26,620 --> 00:27:29,580
Just wait, Usopp! Money!

434
00:27:33,200 --> 00:27:34,410
Really...!

435
00:27:34,410 --> 00:27:37,010
Hey, where's the Franky Family hideout?

436
00:27:37,010 --> 00:27:38,970
It's not really a hideout.

437
00:27:38,970 --> 00:27:44,090
The place is their workshop,
located near where your ship is anchored.

438
00:27:44,090 --> 00:27:47,100
Just follow the coast
northwest from Rocky Cape.

439
00:27:47,100 --> 00:27:49,350
It's called the Franky House.

440
00:27:52,710 --> 00:27:54,610
Luffy!

441
00:27:55,590 --> 00:27:57,760
Luffy!

442
00:27:58,470 --> 00:28:03,160
What gives? As if he could just
run off and find Usopp by himself!

443
00:28:03,840 --> 00:28:06,010
Finding Luffy will have to wait.

444
00:28:06,010 --> 00:28:08,790
I'll take the money back to the ship for now.

445
00:28:09,360 --> 00:28:14,670
Bringing 100 million with me while asking for
200 million is just begging them to take the rest.

446
00:28:15,350 --> 00:28:19,230
Anyway, yagara, please take
the quickest route back to the bull shop!

447
00:28:25,600 --> 00:28:28,560
Zoro and the rest of us
will need to teach them a lesson!

448
00:28:28,560 --> 00:28:33,210
Franky Family! Stealing from
pirates was a bad decision!

449
00:28:39,520 --> 00:28:43,810
Welcome to level one,
the Backstreets shopping district.

450
00:28:43,810 --> 00:28:46,130
Take care and have a good day!

451
00:28:50,040 --> 00:28:51,700
I'm counting on you, yagara!

452
00:28:54,600 --> 00:28:56,130
What the heck?!

453
00:28:56,580 --> 00:28:58,750
Hey, watch out, lady!

454
00:28:58,750 --> 00:29:00,640
Sorry!

455
00:29:01,710 --> 00:29:05,970
Usopp... Tell me you somehow got away.

456
00:29:19,110 --> 00:29:20,490
This is terrible.

457
00:29:20,490 --> 00:29:21,790
Who the heck is he?

458
00:29:21,790 --> 00:29:24,070
Hey! Does anyone know who this guy is?!

459
00:29:24,070 --> 00:29:25,800
A crowd of people...

460
00:29:25,800 --> 00:29:28,030
Wait, yagara! Stop! Stop!

461
00:29:34,700 --> 00:29:36,120
Usopp!

462
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:40,380
Usopp! Wake up!

463
00:29:40,380 --> 00:29:42,840
Hey! Are you okay?!

464
00:29:42,840 --> 00:29:43,920
C'mon!

465
00:29:43,920 --> 00:29:47,000
C'mon! Usopp! Usopp!

466
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:49,830
So hey, you guys
wouldn't happen to be pirates?

467
00:29:49,830 --> 00:29:52,630
Shut up! Don't just stand there gawking!

468
00:29:54,300 --> 00:29:58,230
Usopp! Was it the Franky Family
who did this to you? Was it them?!

469
00:30:01,490 --> 00:30:05,750
Yeah... I was too weak.

470
00:30:06,610 --> 00:30:08,300
Our money...

471
00:30:08,300 --> 00:30:10,160
they took it all.

472
00:30:12,500 --> 00:30:14,010
Nami...

473
00:30:14,010 --> 00:30:15,000
Yeah?

474
00:30:16,410 --> 00:30:20,790
The crew... I can't face them.

475
00:30:24,600 --> 00:30:29,270
And... we were so close
to having the Merry repaired.

476
00:30:31,990 --> 00:30:35,510
I feel... so ashamed.

477
00:30:37,710 --> 00:30:40,360
Dammit!

478
00:30:41,050 --> 00:30:43,900
Usopp, I get it.

479
00:30:43,900 --> 00:30:48,320
Don't worry about the money.
You can count on us to get it back.

480
00:30:48,320 --> 00:30:53,080
He's hurt pretty bad.
I probably shouldn't move him.

481
00:30:53,700 --> 00:30:56,500
Usopp, stay here for a bit.

482
00:30:56,500 --> 00:31:00,300
I'll hurry back to the ship and get help!

483
00:31:00,300 --> 00:31:02,880
I'll bring Chopper, too,
so that he can treat you!

484
00:31:02,880 --> 00:31:05,390
Please don't worry about the money!

485
00:31:05,390 --> 00:31:08,370
I heard their hideout is just up ahead.

486
00:31:08,370 --> 00:31:10,560
We'll crush them and put an end to this!

487
00:31:12,050 --> 00:31:16,060
Hey! This isn't a show!

488
00:31:16,900 --> 00:31:19,520
Listen, Usopp. Just stay put, okay?

489
00:31:20,400 --> 00:31:22,140
I'll be right back!

490
00:31:26,940 --> 00:31:30,240
Get the lead out, yagara!

491
00:31:32,990 --> 00:31:35,580
Ahh! A runaway bull!

492
00:31:34,890 --> 00:31:35,580
Hey!

493
00:31:37,620 --> 00:31:42,290
And... we were so close
to having the Merry repaired.

494
00:31:44,040 --> 00:31:48,710
All the money in the world can't
return your ship to its original state.

495
00:31:49,800 --> 00:31:53,470
Whether we decide to buy a new ship...

496
00:31:53,470 --> 00:31:57,390
or find someone who's willing
to fix and improve the Merry,

497
00:31:57,390 --> 00:32:01,890
we've got to spend the entire 300 million
to upgrade or get a new ship.

498
00:32:01,890 --> 00:32:04,230
The seas will only get rougher from here.

499
00:32:05,340 --> 00:32:07,990
We definitely need that money.

500
00:32:07,990 --> 00:32:09,690
We have to get it back!

501
00:32:12,700 --> 00:32:14,280
Is that true?!

502
00:32:14,280 --> 00:32:17,240
At least that's what that shipwright said.

503
00:32:19,290 --> 00:32:20,580
This ship...

504
00:32:20,580 --> 00:32:23,500
...can no longer be fixed?
Even if we have the money?!

505
00:32:23,500 --> 00:32:26,460
Then, what'll happen to the Merry?!

506
00:32:26,460 --> 00:32:27,910
Beats me.

507
00:32:27,910 --> 00:32:32,720
In the end, it all depends on how Luffy,
Nami, and Usopp react to the assessment.

508
00:32:33,600 --> 00:32:37,600
Those three at the shipyard
will probably come up with a solution.

509
00:32:37,600 --> 00:32:40,890
I don't buy it. It seems really sudden.

510
00:32:40,890 --> 00:32:44,100
Look at the ship! She's the same old Merry.

511
00:32:44,100 --> 00:32:48,650
From the East Blue to here,
we were with Merry the whole way!

512
00:32:48,650 --> 00:32:51,490
But that's exactly the reason.

513
00:32:51,490 --> 00:32:54,280
Humans endure hardship
and become more resilient;

514
00:32:55,050 --> 00:32:56,700
ships are different.

515
00:32:56,700 --> 00:32:59,410
They accumulate stress and damage.

516
00:33:03,850 --> 00:33:05,540
It's hard to swallow.

517
00:33:05,540 --> 00:33:09,100
Besides, how's Usopp gonna react
when he hears this?

518
00:33:09,100 --> 00:33:11,610
But, I love the Going Merry!

519
00:33:11,610 --> 00:33:16,470
We all do. But like that guy said,
her battle scars are too deep.

520
00:33:18,750 --> 00:33:21,440
There's the Going Merry,
but then there's Robin.

521
00:33:22,430 --> 00:33:24,140
What a depressing afternoon.

522
00:33:26,110 --> 00:33:27,790
Guys!

523
00:33:30,250 --> 00:33:32,360
Oh? Nami's back!

524
00:33:32,360 --> 00:33:35,100
Hm? Looks like she's alone.

525
00:33:35,100 --> 00:33:37,030
What happened to Luffy and Usopp?

526
00:33:37,810 --> 00:33:41,540
Nami! Did something happen?!

527
00:33:45,750 --> 00:33:49,690
Yow! Yow, yow!
Did you say "200 million"?!

528
00:33:49,690 --> 00:33:51,590
Yes, 200 million!

529
00:33:51,590 --> 00:33:54,510
Whatcha think, Bro?!

530
00:33:54,510 --> 00:33:57,890
Amazing! You guys are amazing!

531
00:33:57,890 --> 00:34:03,390
With this much cash, we can finally
get the thing we've always wanted!

532
00:34:03,390 --> 00:34:05,490
We did it, didn't we, Bro?

533
00:34:05,490 --> 00:34:09,130
After three long years!
You'd always say, "Once I get the money..."

534
00:34:09,130 --> 00:34:11,020
– It took so long.
– Yeah.

535
00:34:11,020 --> 00:34:15,390
Each time we got a chunk of money,
we'd pin our hopes on yagara races...

536
00:34:15,390 --> 00:34:16,900
– ...and end up broke!
– ...and end up broke!

537
00:34:16,900 --> 00:34:20,600
Each time we captured a criminal
with a bounty, we'd party it up...

538
00:34:20,600 --> 00:34:22,160
– ...and end up broke!
– ...and end up broke!

539
00:34:22,160 --> 00:34:27,210
We couldn't quite save up
the 200-million-belly business expense!

540
00:34:27,210 --> 00:34:29,130
But we finally got it all!

541
00:34:29,130 --> 00:34:33,150
Oh, yeah! You guys pulled through big time!

542
00:34:33,840 --> 00:34:38,510
Well then, it ain't much,
but here's five million belly.

543
00:34:38,510 --> 00:34:42,140
I want to show you my appreciation,
so eat, drink, and be merry!

544
00:34:46,300 --> 00:34:48,010
That's our Bro!

545
00:34:48,010 --> 00:34:49,730
It's party time!

546
00:34:57,010 --> 00:34:58,900
Wh-What the hell?!

547
00:34:59,800 --> 00:35:00,660
Hm?

548
00:35:01,200 --> 00:35:02,700
Aw, dammit!

549
00:35:02,700 --> 00:35:07,830
Who're you?! You wanna dance
with the Franky Family?!

550
00:35:13,090 --> 00:35:16,610
Huh?! You're that string bean from earlier!

551
00:35:16,610 --> 00:35:18,550
How the hell are you still standing?!

552
00:35:22,300 --> 00:35:24,010
Give me back the money!

553
00:35:24,010 --> 00:35:30,060
"Give me back the money"?
So, you're one of Straw Hat's goons?

554
00:35:31,310 --> 00:35:33,560
That's right, Bro!

555
00:35:33,560 --> 00:35:39,010
Since he's with Straw Hat Luffy,
we expected him to be a real tough pirate...

556
00:35:39,010 --> 00:35:41,280
...but it turns out he's just a weak punk!

557
00:35:41,920 --> 00:35:44,240
As if you'd understand anything!

558
00:35:45,620 --> 00:35:46,740
Whoa there!

559
00:35:51,610 --> 00:35:53,040
Is he for real?!

560
00:35:53,040 --> 00:35:56,810
I'll admit you've got guts to come
and get the money back all by yourself,

561
00:35:56,810 --> 00:35:59,630
but I can't let you have it.

562
00:36:02,910 --> 00:36:04,890
Give it back!

563
00:36:04,890 --> 00:36:11,200
We have to... have our ship repaired.

564
00:36:14,480 --> 00:36:17,020
We desperately need that money!

565
00:36:21,490 --> 00:36:25,080
With that money, we can finally...

566
00:36:25,080 --> 00:36:30,620
We can finally mend
the Going Merry's wounds!

567
00:36:30,620 --> 00:36:35,870
This money... I won't let you assholes take it!

568
00:36:41,680 --> 00:36:43,630
What's got you all worked up?

569
00:36:44,500 --> 00:36:48,190
I see you really love your ship.

570
00:36:48,190 --> 00:36:52,640
Well! It doesn't matter what
happens to your ship anymore.

571
00:36:52,640 --> 00:36:56,560
This money belongs to us now.

572
00:36:58,520 --> 00:37:04,090
Unfortunately for you, no matter what we steal
from pirates, we won't be accused of committing a crime.

573
00:37:04,090 --> 00:37:07,780
Let me guess! It's dirty money
you stole, ain't it?

574
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:11,200
So, just let us keep it.

575
00:37:13,210 --> 00:37:16,670
You could always beg the Marines for help.

576
00:37:16,670 --> 00:37:19,390
But you'll probably be the ones arrested.

577
00:37:20,810 --> 00:37:23,610
It's a shame that Straw Hat Luffy...

578
00:37:23,610 --> 00:37:29,640
has such a useless underling
who can't even guard his money.

579
00:37:37,100 --> 00:37:41,240
Guys, go ahead and show him a good time.

580
00:37:42,570 --> 00:37:47,280
Right now, I'm gonna take
this money out for a little shopping!

581
00:37:48,060 --> 00:37:49,530
I can't wait!

582
00:37:49,530 --> 00:37:50,490
Not so fast!

583
00:37:50,490 --> 00:37:53,200
Lethal Exploding Star!

584
00:38:00,750 --> 00:38:05,720
Remember this, long-nosed boy.
My name is Franky.

585
00:38:05,720 --> 00:38:11,950
If you want to leave this town alive,
wise up and never cross me.

586
00:38:14,600 --> 00:38:18,940
What... What're you doing?! Let go of me!

587
00:38:22,510 --> 00:38:26,320
A puny weapon like this won't work on us!

588
00:38:26,950 --> 00:38:29,280
See ya, long-nose.

589
00:38:29,280 --> 00:38:32,790
Thanks for the 200 million belly.

590
00:38:32,790 --> 00:38:36,100
Stop! Give it back to me!

591
00:38:36,100 --> 00:38:37,250
Give it back!

592
00:38:38,100 --> 00:38:39,460
Give it baaack!

593
00:38:49,290 --> 00:38:50,970
Give it... back.

594
00:38:50,970 --> 00:38:53,260
Give it... baaack!

595
00:39:05,440 --> 00:39:08,900
Give... it... back!

596
00:39:10,870 --> 00:39:15,070
Give it baaaaaack!

597
00:39:24,730 --> 00:39:27,090
I just have to hold out
until Robin comes back.

598
00:39:30,430 --> 00:39:33,640
I'd just get in the way
if I marched in with the others.

599
00:39:34,510 --> 00:39:35,600
And I'm scared.

600
00:39:37,590 --> 00:39:42,100
At any rate, I'll do anything
to protect this ship and the 100 million belly.

601
00:39:42,100 --> 00:39:44,270
The rest is in your hands...

602
00:39:44,270 --> 00:39:45,930
you guys!

603
00:39:47,040 --> 00:39:49,100
Stop. Stop!

604
00:39:52,710 --> 00:39:57,510
If I remember right, this should be
the place Nami was talking about.

605
00:39:59,690 --> 00:40:02,380
Look. This is the Backstreets shopping district.

606
00:40:02,380 --> 00:40:07,600
You go up this canal... and here!
Usopp is right here.

607
00:40:07,600 --> 00:40:08,930
Okay.

608
00:40:08,930 --> 00:40:13,200
So, Nami, where can we find these
demolition workers, the Franky Family?

609
00:40:14,600 --> 00:40:16,000
Usopp!

610
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:17,210
Usopp isn't here?

611
00:40:17,210 --> 00:40:19,800
Are you sure? Maybe you
screwed up the directions.

612
00:40:19,800 --> 00:40:21,770
Look who's talking, swordsmoron!

613
00:40:21,770 --> 00:40:23,400
Usopp!

614
00:40:23,400 --> 00:40:26,110
– What'd you say?!
– Oh!

615
00:40:29,500 --> 00:40:31,280
Look! It's blood!

616
00:40:31,280 --> 00:40:34,820
That dumbass! He walked off
before we got here!

617
00:40:34,820 --> 00:40:37,160
He couldn't have, right?

618
00:40:37,630 --> 00:40:39,620
Usopp.

619
00:40:40,690 --> 00:40:47,250
Ahhh...

620
00:40:42,080 --> 00:40:43,250
Huh?

621
00:40:47,250 --> 00:40:48,050
...ahhh!

622
00:40:54,300 --> 00:40:55,560
Help me!

623
00:40:55,560 --> 00:40:57,010
Luffy?!

624
00:41:03,820 --> 00:41:07,720
What're you doing?!
Where'd you come falling from?

625
00:41:08,850 --> 00:41:10,200
The shipyard...

626
00:41:10,200 --> 00:41:14,280
I was copying that shipwright,
jumping around to look for Usopp.

627
00:41:14,280 --> 00:41:15,450
Are you okay?

628
00:41:15,450 --> 00:41:16,820
Yeah.

629
00:41:16,820 --> 00:41:19,560
Oh, that's right, guys! We've got a problem!

630
00:41:19,560 --> 00:41:21,750
Usopp got taken, along with the money!

631
00:41:22,310 --> 00:41:23,930
Yeah, we know.

632
00:41:23,930 --> 00:41:27,960
Come on. We're headed to their hideout.

633
00:41:27,960 --> 00:41:30,700
They beat up Usopp
and took the money.

634
00:41:30,700 --> 00:41:31,670
What?!

635
00:41:33,600 --> 00:41:35,530
Maybe he blamed himself...

636
00:41:35,530 --> 00:41:40,170
and left all on his own
to confront the Franky Family.

637
00:42:02,410 --> 00:42:04,890
Is he breathing, Chopper?

638
00:42:04,890 --> 00:42:07,300
He's fallen unconscious...

639
00:42:07,300 --> 00:42:09,090
he's not dead yet.

640
00:42:09,090 --> 00:42:11,460
He'll be okay. I can save him.

641
00:42:16,490 --> 00:42:18,760
Just rest there a moment...

642
00:42:18,760 --> 00:42:20,550
Usopp.

643
00:42:44,310 --> 00:42:48,390
We're gonna go demolish that stupid house.

